    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our offensive core is anchored by **Corbin Carroll** (84.46) and **Jose Caballero** (71.89), our top-scoring options who leverage high-end sprint speed to exploit favorable matchup dynamics. **Corbin Carroll** is our clear headliner; he benefits from a massive park boost and a high-leverage #2 slot in the order. Meanwhile, **Jose Caballero** represents a high-upside play against Yusei Kikuchi, gaining a 13% efficiency bump from a dynamic platoon advantage. While his #9 spot in the lineup is a structural drag, his ability to manipulate the basepaths against the Kikuchi-led battery makes him a critical component of our strategy to win the scarcest category: Stolen Bases. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (67.91) and **Giancarlo Stanton** (65.85) also profile as high-tier starts in the same matchup, as we look to capitalize on the favorable wind conditions pushing balls out of the yard.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Max Muncy** (45.06), who hovered near our start threshold but ultimately fell short. While **Max Muncy** benefits from a park-factor boost against Nathan Eovaldi, the combination of Eovaldi\u2019s sub-3.20 xERA and the optimizer\u2019s preference for the defensive versatility and speed-first profiles of our middle infielders kept him sidelined. We remain cautious regarding **James Wood** (48.75) and **Seiya Suzuki** (50.33); both face sub-3.15 xERA arms today, which severely suppresses their base projections. We are banking on their top-of-the-order positioning\u2014specifically **James Wood** in the leadoff spot\u2014to mitigate the risk posed by the elite strikeout stuff of Paul Skenes and Cristopher S\u00e1nchez. Owners should monitor all lineups closely, as the \"Lineup Pending\" status for **Dalton Rushing** and **Alex Freeland** introduces variance that could force a re-optimization if they are dropped into lower-leverage spots or held out of the starting nine entirely.",
